  "summary": "Hercule Poirot discusses Alistair Brent's personal views, noting Brent's dislike for a young man involved in subversive activities. To determine potential beneficiaries of Brent's estate, Poirot inquires about his assets. Brent reveals that his will primarily benefits St. Edward's Hospital, the Cancer Hospital, and the Royal Blind Institute. He also leaves money to his wife's niece, Julia Olivia Lady; a trust for her daughter, Jane Olivia; and a sum to his distant cousin, Helen Montresor, who resides in a local farmhouse. Brent officially commissions Poirot to locate Miss Mabel Sainsbury-Sil.\n\nUpon leaving, Poirot is insulted by Jane Olivia, who calls him a \"meddling spy\" and a \"damned bourgeois detective,\" asserting that her uncle is safe. He also encounters Lady Olivia, who treats him with disdain. While walking in the garden at night, Poirot observes Brent dictating notes to Mr. Selby. Later, in his room, Poirot reflects on several confusing elements, including a telephone call, Mr. Barnes, Albert Chapman, and the maid Agnes, noting that the circumstances surrounding Sainsbury-Sil remain particularly contradictory.\n\nThe following morning, Poirot observes Helen Montresor speaking sarcastically to a gardener in a gruff Scottish voice. He then approaches a young gardener who is digging vigorously and appears reluctant to engage in conversation. Poirot finds the young man's behavior and physical presence strange and interesting, observing him from behind a garden wall.",
